# ZWO guider deployment

## W. Schoenell, Aug 2025

This document describes the deployment of the new ZWO guiders at the Magellan Telescopes. 

The deployment has a few modules:

- Nanotech motors: Connected via an EtherNET connection, they can be controlled by ModBUS-TCP protocol. The UI and code can be found in the following repositories:  
  Back-end: [http://gitlab.lco.cl/hwcontrol/guider\_linux](http://gitlab.lco.cl/hwcontrol/guider_linux)  
  Front-end: [http://gitlab.lco.cl/hwcontrol/guider\_linux/guider-linux-gui](http://gitlab.lco.cl/hwcontrol/guider_linux/guider-linux-gui)  
- Raspberry Pi operating system: loads remotely from a network server. It has been done this way to facilitate the deployment of multiple ZWO guiders, and to avoid the usage of SD cards, which are unreliable for deployments like this (more than 30 hosts). The deployment is automated using ansible playbooks available in this repository: [https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/lco-ansible](https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/lco-ansible)  
- ZWO Server: Controls the ZWO cameras and provides images to the GCAM software. [https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/zwo/tree/main/src/server](https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/zwo/tree/main/src/server)  
- ZWO GCAM: Guider camera software, receives data from the server and sends guiding offsets to TCS and others.  
  [https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/zwo/tree/main/src/gcam](https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/zwo/tree/main/src/gcam)  
- GMAP: Guider start map selection tool.  
  git@gitlab.lco.cl:magop/magsoft.git

There are a few other scripts that translate the commands from the TCS to the GCAM, instruments and vice-versa. These scripts are good candidates for being incorporated into current software, making it less prone to failures.

- GCAM2ZWO: Receives commands from EDS to GCAM/ZWO.  
  [http://gitlab.lco.cl/magop/magsoft/-/blob/devel/eds/gcam2zwo.py](http://gitlab.lco.cl/magop/magsoft/-/blob/devel/eds/gcam2zwo.py)  
- GPC2IMACS: Receives commands from EDS and forwards them to IMACS instrument  
  [http://gitlab.lco.cl/magop/magsoft/-/blob/devel/eds/gpc2imacs.py](http://gitlab.lco.cl/magop/magsoft/-/blob/devel/eds/gpc2imacs.py)

## Deployment of a new guider

To deploy a new guider, follow the documentation in the [README](https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/lco-ansible/blob/main/README.md) of the lco-ansible repository. The steps that must be followed are:

- Before installing the raspberry pi:  
  - Boot it with an SD card and collect the following information into the inventory:  
    ansible\_host: This is the Raspberry Pi IP address  
    mac: This is the wired network MAC address  
    tftp\_sn: This can be obtained from the vcgencmd otp\_dump | grep 28: command output. See [README](https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/lco-ansible/blob/main/README.md) for more information.  
    switch\_ip: IP of the switch this guider is connected to (if using POE powercylcing)  
    switch\_snmp\_community: SNMP community of the switch  
    switch\_port: Switchport where the this server is connected to.  
    zwo\_sn: S/N of the connected ZWO camera  
- Update the EEPROM of the Raspberry to the latest version and set the boot order for TFTP boot, following the [README](https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/lco-ansible/blob/main/README.md).

- Install the raspberry pi on the switch and run the ansible playbooks for deploying the raspberry pi operating system and deploying the raspberry pi zwo server application. See [README](https://github.com/carnegie-observatories/lco-ansible/blob/main/README.md) for more information.  
- Test the installation. Boot of the raspberry pi can be followed by the logs on the boot server (using `journalctl \-f`)


  

## POE power analysis

During the development of the POE+TFTP boot solution, power consumption tests were done in the lab and they showed that the chosen HAT meets the requirements. The results are documented in [this document](zwo_power_measurement.html).
